```latex
\paragraph{Tools Take the Lead.}
We first consider the case where the tool latency in each round is much larger than the model's generation latency:
\begin{equation}
t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i) \gg t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i).
\end{equation}
In this regime, the generation time has a negligible impact on test-time compute.
Therefore, under a fixed time budget $t_{\mathrm{budget}}$, the number of interaction rounds $N$ is largely determined by tool latency:
\begin{equation}
N \approx \frac{t_{\mathrm{budget}}}{t_{\mathrm{tool}}}.
\end{equation}
Consequently, the per-round interaction quality becomes the key factor that determines task performance.
For such tasks, the model should be encouraged to reason more carefully within each round, ensuring that every tool call yields useful progress.

\paragraph{Models Take the Lead.}
In some scenarios, tool latency is negligible, or the model can solve the task without any tool use:
\begin{equation}
t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i) \gg t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i).
\end{equation}
In this case, test-time compute collapses back to the conventional setting, where the total cost is dominated by the number of generated tokens.
Imposing a longer (or shorter) time limit is effectively equivalent to allocating a larger (or smaller) token budget.
```

```latex
\subsection{Meeting in the Middle}
In more general settings, the model's generation latency and the tool-call latency are often of a similar scale, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i) \approx t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i).
\end{equation}
In this regime, test-time compute is jointly determined by tool latency and generation latency.
We define a per-step latency ratio
\begin{equation}
m_i = \frac{t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i)}{t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i)}.
\end{equation}
Then the tool-call time at step $i$ can be written as $t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i) = m_i \cdot t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i)$, and the total cost becomes
\begin{equation}
t_{\mathrm{all}} = \sum_{i=1}^{N} (m_i + 1)\, t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i).
\end{equation}

Crucially, neither $t_{\mathrm{gen}}(i)$ nor $t_{\mathrm{tool}}(i)$ is known in advance at the beginning of step $i$.
As a result, $m_i$ is a random variable that may fluctuate substantially across steps.
When $m_i > 1$, tool latency dominates; it is then beneficial to encourage the model to reason more thoroughly within each round, so that each tool call is of higher quality.
When $m_i < 1$, generation latency dominates; the model may instead shorten its reasoning to enable more rounds of tool interaction and obtain more feedback.
Because $m_i$ is volatile, static strategies that adjust computation solely based on the number of generated tokens cannot adapt well to such tasks.

Therefore, for most tool-use scenarios where $m_i$ is both fluctuating and unpredictable, the notion of test-time compute in agentic tasks should be directly tied to time as a physical quantity.
Only when an LLM can dynamically regulate its behavior based on environment feedback can an agent system built on top of it effectively adapt its reasoning strategy to different test-time budgets.
```

